The Data

The data set for this assignment consists of college admissions data. It comes from an open data set available via https://www.kaggle.com/mohansacharya/graduate-admissions .

The dataset contains several parameters which are considered important during the application for Masters Programs. The parameters included are:

  1. GRE Scores ( out of 340 )
  2. TOEFL Scores ( out of 120 )
  3. University Rating ( out of 5 )
  4. Statement of Purpose and Letter of Recommendation Strength ( out of 5 )
  5. Undergraduate GPA ( out of 10 )
  6. Research Experience ( either 0 or 1 )
  7. Chance of Admit ( ranging from 0 to 1 )

The full citation for the data is:

Mohan S Acharya, Asfia Armaan, Aneeta S Antony : A Comparison of Regression Models for Prediction of Graduate Admissions, IEEE International Conference on Computational Intelligence in Data Science 2019.

Copy the file Admission_Predict.csv from the read only folder into your working directory, fill in your name into the string assigned to MY_UNIQNAME , then execute the following code block to load the packages and data into your environment.

MY_UNIQNAME = "Tabbie"

# Initial setup for our environment
library(tidyverse)

library(moderndive)

# Reading the file in from your working directory
data <- read_csv('Admission_Predict.csv')
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   `Serial No.` = col_double(),
##   `GRE Score` = col_double(),
##   `TOEFL Score` = col_double(),
##   `University Rating` = col_double(),
##   SOP = col_double(),
##   LOR = col_double(),
##   CGPA = col_double(),
##   Research = col_double(),
##   `Chance of Admit` = col_double()
## )
data <- data %>% select(gre = "GRE Score", toefl = "TOEFL Score", university_rating = `University Rating`, sop = SOP, lor = LOR, cgpa = CGPA, research=Research,admit = `Chance of Admit`) %>% mutate(research=factor(research))

Question 1 (5 points)

Explain what the previous R code block does.

Q1 Response:

In the above code from the original dataframe a new dataframe is made named data. From the original dataframe the following columns are selected and renamed; GRE Score is renamed as gre, TOEFL Score is renamed as toefl, University Rating is renamed as university_rating, SOP as sop, LOR as lor, CGPA as cgpa, Research as research, Chance of Admit as admit. Then the mutate function is used to create a new column research with factor type values.

Question 2 (10 points)

Describe the shape of the distribution of the chance of admission. If you decide to use a histogram choose your width of your bins carefully.

data %>% summarise(max_val = max(admit), min_val = min(admit), mean_val = mean(admit), median_val = median(admit))
## # A tibble: 1 x 4
##   max_val min_val mean_val median_val
##     <dbl>   <dbl>    <dbl>      <dbl>
## 1    0.97    0.34    0.724       0.73
ggplot(data = data, mapping = aes(x = admit)) + geom_histogram(bins = 20, binwidth = 0.03, color = 'white', fill = 'darkgreen')

Q2 Response:

The distribution is slightly skewed to the left with a number of lower values of the data on the left side of the histogram. But since a large number of values are seen on the right side of the histogram the skewness is balanced out. We can also notice that the mean and median are fairly same upto the first decimal position.

Question 3 (10 points)

Create a plot of chance of admission as the outcome variable vs.GRE score as the explanatory variable that shows the line of best fit. Label your axes and use a title or caption for the visualization. Does the lowest GRE score have the least chance of admission?

ggplot(data = data, mapping = aes(x = gre, y = admit)) +
  geom_point(size = 1) +
  labs(x = "GRE Score", y = "Chance of Admit", title = 'Representaion of Chance of Admit vs Gre Score') +
  geom_smooth(method="lm",se=FALSE)

ggplot(data = data, mapping = aes(x = gre, y = admit)) +
  geom_jitter(size = 0.8) +
  labs(x = "GRE Score", y = "Chance of Admit", title = 'Representaion of Chance of Admit vs Gre Score') +
  geom_smooth(method="lm",se=FALSE)

Q3 Response:

Yes, the data points with low gre scores show low chances of admit. Although there are few data points with high gre scores show low chances of admit but they very less in number.

Question 5 (10 points)

Create a visualization that shows the relationship between Cumulative GPA and the Chance of Admission.
Use two different colors of lines to show the difference that having research experience makes.
Describe the effect that having research experience appears to have.

ggplot(data = data, mapping = aes(x = cgpa, y = admit, color = research)) +
  geom_jitter(size = 0.8) +
  labs(x = "CGPA", y = "Chance of Admit", color = "Research Experience", title = "Relationship between CGPA and Chance of Admit") +
  geom_smooth(method="lm",se=FALSE)

ggplot(data = data, mapping = aes(x = cgpa, y = admit, color = research)) +
  geom_point(size = 0.8) +
  labs(x = "CGPA", y = "Chance of Admit", color = "Research Experience", title = "Relationship between CGPA and Chance of Admit") +
  geom_smooth(method="lm",se=FALSE)

Q5 Response:

Its generally seen that those applicants having higher CGPA along with research experience have greater chance of admit. Thus, having a research experience positively influence the chance of admit.

Question 6 (15 points)

Create a regression model that uses chance of admission as the outcome variable and Cumulative GPA and research experience as the explanatory variables. What is the expected (estimated) value of the chance of admission for an individual with a cumulative GPA of 9.0 who has research experience.

# Get regression model
data_model2 <- lm(admit ~ cgpa*research, data = data)

summary(data_model2)

Q6 Response:

admit = A + B (cgpa) + C (research) + D (cgpa)(research) admit = -0.8 + (0.18)(9) + (-0.15)(1) + (0.02)(9)(1) admit = 0.85

The expected (estimated) value of the chance of admission for an individual with a cumulative GPA of 9.0 who has research experience is 0.85.
